.TH "ELEMENT.SETATTRIBUTENS" "3JS" "December 19, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Element.setAttributeNS \- Element: setAttributeNS() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Warning:\f[R] This method can take attribute values that are parsed
as HTML, a script, or as a script URL, depending on the attribute.
APIs like this are known as injection sinks, and are potentially a
vector for cross\-site scripting (XSS) attacks, if the value originally
came from an attacker.
.PP
You can mitigate this risk by always passing the appropriate trusted
type object (\f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R], \f[CR]TrustedScript\f[R], or
\f[CR]TrustedScriptURL\f[R]) instead of strings for those attributes
that require them, and enforcing trusted types.
See Security considerations in \f[CR]Element.setAttribute()\f[R] for
more information.
.RE
.PP
The \f[B]\f[CB]setAttributeNS()\f[B]\f[R] method of the
\f[CR]Element\f[R] interface adds a new attribute or changes the value
of an attribute with the given namespace and name.
.PP
If you are working with HTML documents and you don\(cqt need to specify
the requested attribute as being part of a specific namespace, use the
\f[CR]setAttribute()\f[R] method instead.
.PP
Note that \f[CR]setAttributeNS()\f[R] is the only method for namespaced
attributes which expects the fully qualified name, i.e.,
\f[CR]\(dqnamespace:local\-name\(dq\f[R].
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
setAttributeNS(namespace, name, value)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]namespace\f[R]
A string specifying the namespace of the attribute.
.TP
\f[B]name\f[R]
A string identifying the attribute by its qualified name; that is, a
namespace prefix followed by a colon followed by a local name.
.TP
\f[B]value\f[R]
A trusted type or string containing the value to assign to the
attribute.
.RS
.PP
Trusted type instances must be passed for the following attributes when
trusted types are enforced:
.IP \(bu 2
Event handler content attributes, such as \f[CR]onclick\f[R] and
\f[CR]onload\f[R], require a \f[CR]TrustedScript\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]HTMLIFrameElement.srcdoc\f[R] require a \f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R]
instance.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]HTMLScriptElement.src\f[R] require a \f[CR]TrustedScriptURL\f[R]
instance.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]SVGScriptElement.href\f[R] require a \f[CR]TrustedScriptURL\f[R]
instance.
.PP
Trusted types are not enforced for other attributes, so a string or any
trusted type may be passed.
.RE
.SS Return value
None (\f[CR]undefined\f[R]).
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Basic usage
.IP
.EX
\f[B]let\f[R] d = document.getElementById(\(dqd1\(dq);
d.setAttributeNS(
  \(dqhttp://www.mozilla.org/ns/specialspace\(dq,
  \(dqspec:align\(dq,
  \(dqcenter\(dq,
);
.EE
.SS Trusted types
The Setting unsafe attributes example in \f[CR]setAttribute()\f[R] shows
how you might use \f[CR]setAttributeNS()\f[R] with the trusted types.
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Element.hasAttributeNS()\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Element.getAttributeNS()\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Element.removeAttributeNS()\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Element.setAttribute()\f[R]
